00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:20.370
And that's just a really powerful primitive that they can be

00:08:20.370 --> 00:08:20.920
building on.

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:24.740
Um, last week, the verge reported that Google is re

00:08:24.740 --> 00:08:27.790
writing headlines with AI in search results.

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:31.000
Um, I, I quote posted their, their post about

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.400
that and said, uh, this shit is why I'm

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:35.980
a journalism on AT proto extremist.

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:38.280
Um, so like, I'm, I'm, I

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:41.770
'm a believer, but I also get why they're not

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:42.040
.

00:08:42.040 --> 00:08:45.410
And so when I say I'm an AT proto extremist

00:08:45.410 --> 00:08:48.440
, um, for journalism, I'm not talking about just

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:51.200
be having an account on blue sky and linking to your journalism

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:51.350
.

00:08:51.350 --> 00:08:53.780
I mean, putting your journalism on the protocol.

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:54.320
Right.

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:55.780
Um, and like standard.

00:08:55.890 --> 00:08:59.590
site is a really exciting community that offers us some affordances

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:00.080
to do that.

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:02.020
Um, but I think there's some things that are missing

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:02.220
.

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:02.670
Right.

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:06.980
So, um, first standard site has no concept of auth

00:09:07.090 --> 00:09:07.870
orship.

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:10.920
Um, and I think that's, uh, partially because

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:15.240
the I love the leaflet and pocket and off print folks

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:17.800
, they're focused on like solo bloggers for most of

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:18.340
the time.

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:21.390
Uh, whereas news organizations have many authors and, and many

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:22.120
contributors.

00:09:22.120 --> 00:09:24.830
And like, you need a way to describe those relationships.

00:09:24.830 --> 00:09:27.060
What desk does this person work for?

00:09:27.060 --> 00:09:28.520
Are they a freelancer?

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:31.800
Uh, we need better ways on protocol of describing those relationships

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:35.330
for every individual document, um, and who worked on them

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:35.580
.

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:37.610
Uh, and then also the content lexicon thing is

00:09:37.610 --> 00:09:40.350
, is a real, uh, problem to be solved.

00:09:40.350 --> 00:09:42.760
Uh, it was announced yesterday that I, uh, am

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:45.010
receiving a small grant from the community fund.

00:09:45.010 --> 00:09:47.050
Thank you to the community fund.

00:09:47.050 --> 00:09:52.130
Um, uh, and I'm trying to work in this

00:09:52.210 --> 00:09:55.310
space of like, how can we describe news content on the

00:09:55.310 --> 00:09:58.360
protocol, uh, and work within, uh, the bounds

00:09:58.360 --> 00:09:59.010
of standard.

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:00.140
site for that.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.380
Um, even if we had all that, the thing that

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:08.130
is really missing is, like, a premium news reading experience

00:10:08.130 --> 00:10:10.170
that's built on top of standard.

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:10.660
site.

00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:13.960
Um, I, I talk a lot about Apple news on

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:15.320
AT Proto.

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:19.360
Um, Apple news offers a ton of reach.

00:10:19.360 --> 00:10:21.480
Um, and I, I know this because I've implemented

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:24.290
Apple news at publications I've worked at, um, where

00:10:24.290 --> 00:10:26.800
, uh, we would get a story promoted on Apple news

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:29.710
and it would just dwarf the traffic we got to our main

00:10:29.710 --> 00:10:30.170
site.

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:32.160
Like orders of magnitude higher.

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:35.780
Um, but Apple news offered no way to, other than

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:40.680
following the publication on Apple news to deepen your relationship with a

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:41.290
reader.

00:10:41.290 --> 00:10:43.620
And, uh, so we never were able to get them

00:10:43.620 --> 00:10:46.710
to subscribe to our newsletters, to donate, to

00:10:46.710 --> 00:10:47.620
become members.

00:10:47.620 --> 00:10:50.280
Like there was just no facility for doing that stuff.

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:52.980
I think it was just such a huge opportunity.

00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:56.440
If we can get the content on protocol and tell that story

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:02.010
to build a news aggregator that is actually owned and operated

00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:06.510
by news publishers and offers them the opportunity to actually control their

00:11:06.510 --> 00:11:09.070
distribution layer in a way that they'd never been able to

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:09.880
in the digital space.

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:13.240
Um, so that's my pitch at the moment.

00:11:13.240 --> 00:11:17.210
One thing I keep coming back to and when I sit down

00:11:17.210 --> 00:11:19.930
and actually think instead of just get mad about why there's

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:23.600
so many organizations that still really lean into Twitter and even individual

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:25.950
journalists, it's, it's, it really is just

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:27.460
all about the incentives.

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:30.100
And so it feels like there's an opportunity to kind of

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:35.520
move those incentives away from the traditional centralized protocols that we've

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:38.250
got now and, uh, onto something where there's a

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:39.080
lot more ownership.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:41.000
Um, under, I'm kind of curious to get your

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.720
perspective a little bit, um, thinking about those incentives.

